<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-23-0573 </DOCNO><TEXT>In this timely study, the authors analyze the competitiveness of the U.S.auto industry and evaluate the effectiveness of various government policiesaimed at the industry. The authors conclude that the U.S. automobileindustry can achieve competitiveness with foreign producers and maintainhealthy sales through the 1980s without import restrictions. They arguethat the government can support competitiveness by opposing trade restraints,by maintaining an appropriate dollar-yen exchange rate, and by institutingeffective employment adjustment assistance programs. The authors alsofind that, in general, government policies directed toward social problemsrelated to the auto industry have had disappointing results.</TEXT></DOC>